.prelim 'Overview'
..pp;Many publications in an academic environment have a number of
things in common:
..sp;..of 2
* preliminary pages:
a title page or area,
an abstract,
an acknowledgements section or page,
a Table of Contents,
a List of Tables,
and a List of Figures.
..sp;..of 2
* a main body:
chapters and appendices divided into
sections, subsections, and subsubsections,
with tables, figures, block quotations, footnotes, lists of points,
and some additional components such as an index and a bibliography.
..sp;..of
However, different types of documents have different "layout" requiremen
In some cases, the various levels of divisions in the main body must
be numbered (such as chapter "I", section "1.1", and subsection "1.1.1")
in others, such numbering is not required.
In some cases, new chapters must begin on new pages; in others, it isn't
desired.
..pp;The physical layout of a document
is just as important as the concepts and facts it
attempts to convey.
Ensuring that the layout of a document follows a set of standards
necessitates that an identical sequence of layout or "formatting" operat
be performed for each similar item in the document.
This is
..hw time--consuming,
repetitive,
..hw error--prone work.
If the document is being prepared on a
..hw type-writer,
it is also work which
must be re-done with each successive draft.
..pp;SYSPUB is a set of commands designed specifically for use in prepar
formatting papers, theses, and other types of research and instructional
publications common to the university environment.
For years, people have used the computer to perform some of
this work;
SYSPUB offers a number of additional advantages.
..pp
SYSPUB provides 35 different commands for the various components of
your document.
There are also 9 different output formats, called
"layouts".
When you use SYSPUB, you begin by selecting the layout most appropriate
document, but the commands you use thereafter are the same for all layou
The following is a sample input file which
formats a document in the form of a paper:
..sk;..cc begin;..in 4
 .im syspub layout=paper
 .prelim 'Abstract'
 .para
 text of abstract
 .chapter 'Title of First Chapter'
 .para
 text of first paragraph
 .para
 text of second paragraph
 .section 'Title of Section'
 .para
 text of paragraph
 .subsection 'Title of Subsection'
 .para
   .
   .
   .
..in;..cc end
..pp;SYSPUB commands correspond to the component parts of your
document.
For example, to start a new section, you specify
.sp;     .section 'title of section'
.sp;and SYSPUB produces a section heading which conforms to the layout
style you are using.
The same is true for the other SYSPUB commands:
SYSPUB eliminates the need to learn a
..hw widely--accepted
set of layout standards.
..pp;SYSPUB eliminates the
..hw re--numbering
problems caused by revisions.
It does the numbering for all of the above items,
as appropriate to the layout you are using.
If you delete a section, or add a chapter, or change the order of subsec
they are automatically
..hw re--numbered
the next time you format your document.
The creative desire to add or delete information no longer causes
additional "re-work".
..pp;With the simpler layouts, you don't need to use all of the SYSPUB c
For example, most small reports and papers do not have an index or a tab
of contents.
However, with larger documents, such as users' guides and manuals, these
are usually desired.
..pp
SYSPUB also has a number of
..hw specific--purpose
layouts, including layouts for
theses which adhere to the style indicated in the University's
..us Thesis Regulations and Guide
brochure, publications in the style defined in the
..us Publication Manual of the
..us American Psychological Association,
and a layout for papers in the
..hw two--column
format of IEEE
..hw photo--offset
publications.
..pp;When you use SYSPUB, you are actually using a "superset" of the
University of Waterloo version of the SCRIPT text formatter, and all of
capabilities of SCRIPT are available to you.
SYSPUB doesn't do anything which you couldn't do yourself using SCRIPT;
just eliminates the need to learn everything about SCRIPT, and simplifie
a lot of tedious work.
The number of SCRIPT commands which you might need in addition to the SY
commands is very small
(in most cases, the SCRIPT commands which leave a blank line,
centre a line, and underscore a word will be sufficient).
