..pp;SYSPUB assumes that the output is being produced on a 10-pitch devi
(10 characters to the horizontal inch).
If you are using a 12-pitch output device, specify "pitch=12".
..ix 2 'output' 'characters per inch'
..pp;If the final copy of your publication is to be reproduced on both
..ix 2 output 'on both sides of the page'
sides of the page, the "sides" parameter will allow you to specify this.
..pp;The "hy" parameter controls hyphenation:  "on" results in automatic
..ix 2 hyphenation
hyphenation, "full" is the same as "on" but also imbeds the hyphenation
exception dictionary for you, "user" will hyphenate only at hyphen point
defined in the input text (such as in compound words), and "off" causes
hyphenation not to be performed at all.
..pp;The "ju", "pl", and "ll" parameters
..ix 2 output 'line length';..ix 2 output 'page length'
..ix 2 output justified
have the same function as their SCRIPT control-word
equivalents.
..pp;By default, SYSPUB always numbers pages at the bottom of the pages;
..ix numbering pages 'at the top'
the "pagenum" parameter provides a way of having SYSPUB number the pages
at the top, except for preliminary pages and the first page of
each major division of the main body.
..pp;For those layouts which cause the various headings to be numbered,
..ix 2 numbering headings
you can control the level to which headings are numbered by specifying t
"headnum" parameter.
By default, all levels of headings from the first level (chapters and
appendicies) down to the fourth level (subsubsections) are numbered by
those layouts.
For example, specifying "headnum=1" will cause chapters and appendices t
be numbered, but not sections, subsections, or subsubsections.
.section 'Planning Your Publication'
..pp;SYSPUB can be very useful while you are still at the stage of
planning the general organization of your publication.
You can enter the SYSPUB commands to create the major divisions
of the publication, and then
format and print this first-draft "outline" document.
Completing the publication then becomes a process of "filling in the
blanks".
.section 'Using SCRIPT'
..pp;If you are using SCRIPT under CMS, you will probably have to "defin
storage" to at least "400K".
If you are using the BATCH Service, you will have to change your
EXEC card to
..sp;     //  EXEC  SCRIPT,SIZE=200K
..sp;Depending on the size of your publication, you might not need all
200K, but it is safer to start high and work down (the printout will tel
you how much was actually used).
..pp;If you are specifying the "hy=full" parameter, you should add
44K to the above figures.
.section "Using the SYSPUB User's Guide"
.pp;If you are using SYSPUB for the first time, you might find it most
productive to adopt a step-by-step "workbook" approach to using this
User's Guide.
First, select the layout which you suspect is most appropriate for the
publication you are going to prepare,
and read up to the end of the chapter which describes that layout.
Skim over the rest of the User's Guide so that you are aware of
the additional capabilities of SYSPUB.
While you are constructing your publication, treat the entire User's Gui
as a reference manual.
.chapter 'The REPORT Layout'
