.section 'The Title of the Publication'
..ix 2 'title area'
..pp;The publications for which the REPORT layout is intended
do not have a formal Title Page.
Instead, they have a "title area" at the top of the first page, and the
body of the report begins on this page, beneath the title area.
The SYSPUB command
..sp;     .titlepage
..ix 'titlepage'
..sp;is used to start the formatting of the title area.
It is followed, on the next input line, by the title of the publication
(in capital letters and
on as many input lines as are needed),
and by whatever additional text you wish to appear in the title area.
Do not attempt to centre the text on these input lines;
SYSPUB will do that for you, automatically, for all the lines of text
which appear in the title area.
.section 'Starting a Chapter'
..ix 2 headings chapter
..pp;The first-level divisions of the "main body" are called "chapters",
and are created by using the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .chapter 'title'
..ix chapter
..sk;The chapter title will be centered and printed in capital letters.
.section 'Starting a Section'
..ix 2 headings section
..pp;The second-level divisions of a REPORT layout are called "sections"
Sections are defined by using the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .section 'title'
..ix section
..sp;where "title" is the title of the section.
The section title will be printed in uppercase and underscored.
.subsection 'Starting a Subsection'
..ix 2 headings subsection
..pp;A section may be broken into third-level divisions called
"subsections" by using the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .subsection 'title'
..ix subsection
..sp;where "title" is the title of the subsection.
The subsection title will be printed as entered, underscored.
.subsub 'Starting a Subsubsection'
..ix 2 headings subsubsection
..pp;If necessary, subsections may be broken into
"subsubsections" by using the SYSPUB command
..sk;     .subsub 'title'
..ix subsub;..sk
The title will be printed exactly as entered.
.section 'Starting a Paragraph'
..ix 2 paragraphs
..pp;The ".para" command may be used to start a paragraph.
It is used as shown below:
..sp;..cc 4
     .para
     text of paragraph
     .para
     text of next paragraph
..pp;By default, the ".para" command indents each paragraph by putting
3 blanks at the start of the first line of text following the ".para"
command.
This can be changed by specifying an "alternate paragraph indent" as the
operand of the ".para" command.
For example, if
..sp;     .para 5
..sp;is specified, then the ".para" command will indent all paragraphs
5 spaces, from this point on and until the "paragraph indent" is re-set
by another ".para" command with an "alternate paragraph indent" specifie
.section 'Footnotes'
..ix 2 footnotes
..pp;Two SYSPUB commands are provided for the creation of footnotes.
They are used in the manner indicated below:
..sp
     text of the sentence containing the
     .footnote 'word'
     text of the footnote
     .footend
     to be referenced, followed by
     the rest of the sentence, if any.
..sp;For
.footnote 'example,'
This is a sample footnote.
.footend
the first footnote at the bottom of this page was created by
..sp;..cc begin
     For
     .footnote 'example,'
     This is a sample footnote.
     .footend
     the first footnote at the bottom ...
..cc end
.subsection 'Starting the Footnote'
..sp;     .footnote 'word'
..ix 'footnote'
..pp;The "word" to be referenced will be printed on the output line
and the footnote number
will be generated automatically and printed
immediately behind
.footnote 'it.'
If the output is being produced in 'OFFLINE' mode, the footnote numbers
are printed as superscripts.
If the output is being produced in 'ONLINE' mode, the footnote numbers a
printed as normal numbers, in parentheses.
The 'ONLINE' or 'OFFLINE' mode is determined by the SCRIPT options
OFFLINE (or PRINTER or DISK) and ONLINE (or MEMO).
For more information, see Appendix A.
.footend
..pp;If any punctuation is to come between the "word" and the footnote
number, it should be specified as part of the first-operand
"word" to be referenced.
If any punctuation is to be placed
immediately after the footnote number, it must be specified
in quotes as the second operand of the ".footnote" command, as in:
..sp;     .footnote 'word' 'punctuation'
..pp;Because the semicolon is the default SCRIPT
..us control word separator,;it is difficult to cause a
semicolon to be accepted as part of either operand of the ".footnote"
command.  In fact, an error may result if you do not use the SCRIPT ".cw
CONTROL WORD SEPARATOR control word to nullify the control word separato
character, as shown below.
..sp;..cc 3;     .cw
     .footnote 'word' ';'  (or .footnote 'word;')
     text of the footnote
..sp;The ".footnote" command will reset the control word separator back
to the semicolon before it returns to process the text of the footnote.
.subsection 'Underscoring the Word to be Referenced'
..pp;If you want the "word" operand of the ".footnote" command to
be underscored, do it as follows:
..sp;     .footnote '.us word×'
..sp;The vertical bar at the end is essential.
.subsection 'Terminating the Footnote'
..sp;     .footend
..ix 'footend'
..pp;The ".footend" command must follow the text of the footnote.
If the footnote is being used in reference to something in the middle of
a sentence, the rest of that sentence must follow the ".footend" command
.section 'Quotations'
..ix 2 quotations
.pp;The material in this section pertains only to multiple-line
(or "block") quotations;
"in-line" material in quotes (like the preceding words "in-line")
should be entered as normal text, without using the
SYSPUB commands described below.
..pp;To begin the quotation, use the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .quote begin
..ix 'quote' 'begin'
..sp;On the next input lines, enter the text of the quotation.
To terminate the quotation, use the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .quote end
..ix 'quote' 'end'
..sp;For example, the input sequence
..sp;..cc begin
     This is the last sentence preceding the quotation;
     to start the quotation, use ".quote begin".
     .quote begin
     This is the quoted material.
     Note that it is entered without quotes, and is
     automatically indented and single-spaced by SYSPUB.
     .quote end
     To terminate the quotation use ".quote end";
     this is the first sentence after the quotation.
..cc end;..sp;produces:
..sp;..cc begin;This is the last sentence preceding the quotation;
to start the quotation, use ".quote begin".
.quote begin
This is the quoted material.
Note that it is entered without quotes, and is
automatically indented and single-spaced by SYSPUB.
.quote end
To terminate the quotation, use ".quote end";
this is the first sentence after the quotation.
..cc end
.subsection 'Footnotes Inside Quotations'
..ix 2 footnotes 'inside quotations'
..pp;If you want to footnote a "block" quotation, the SYSPUB commands
for the footnote should be used
..us inside;those for the quotation, as shown in the following example:
..sp;..cc begin
     .quote begin
     text of quotation,
     up to but not including the last
     .footnote 'word'
     text of footnote ...
     .footend
     .quote end
..cc end
.section 'Lists of Points'
..ix 2 points
..pp;It is often appropriate to present a sequence of information as a
numbered list of points.
The SYSPUB commands ".point begin", ".point", and ".point end"
may be used to generate such a numbered list.
.subsection 'Starting a List of Points'
     .point begin
..ix 'point' 'begin'
..pp;The SYSPUB command ".point begin" must immediately precede the
input line containing the text for the first
point in a list.
.subsection 'Continuing the List of Points'
     .point
..ix point
..pp;The SYSPUB command ".point" is used to terminate the text of the
preceding point and is followed by the
input line containing the
text of the next point.  The number of the point
will be one greater than the number of the preceding point.
..pp;For example, the input sequence
..sp;..cc begin
     This is the last sentence before the list of points;
     now comes the input to create the list of points.
     .point begin
     This is the text for the first point.
     .point
     This is the text for the next (and last) point.
     .point end
..cc end;..sp;produces:
..sp;This is the last sentence before the list of points;
now comes the input to create the list of points.
.point begin;This is the text for the first point.
.point;This is the text for the next (and last) point.
.point end
.subsection 'Points Within Points'
..ix 2 points 'multiple levels'
..pp;SYSPUB supports three levels of points.
The ".point" command can also be used to begin a second-level point if
you are already in the middle of a list of points.
..sp;     .point 2
..ix point '2'
..sp;will cause SYSPUB to begin creating second-level points, numbered
alphabetically.
To return to the next point at the first level, specify
..sp;     .point 1
..ix point '1'
..sp;and follow it with the text of the next first-level point.
..pp;If you are creating second-level points and want to start creating
third-level points, then specify
..sp;     .point 3
..ix 'point' '3'
..sp;Third-level points are numbered as lower-case roman numerals.
To return to second-level points, specify
..sp;     .point 2
..sp;To return to first-level points from third-level points, specify
..sp;     .point 1
.subsection 'Terminating the List of Points'
     .point end
..ix 'point' 'end'
..pp;The SYSPUB command ".point end" is used after the text of the last
point, to return from the point-formatting mode to the "normal text" mod
.subsection 'Altering the Numbering Style for Lists of Points'
..ix 2 numbering points
..pp;By default, SYSPUB numbers first-level points using arabic numerals
second-level points using lower-case alphabetics, and third-level points
using lower-case roman numerals.
You can change this style by using the "set" operand of the SYSPUB
".point" command.  For example,
..sp;     .point set 1 a i
..ix 'point' 'set'
..sp;will set the point-numbering style to the defaults just described.
..sp;     .point set i a 1
..sp;will cause first-level points to be numbered using lower-case
roman numerals ("i"), second-level points to use lower-case alphabetics
and third-level points to use arabic numerals ("1").
..pp;Operands other than "1", "a", and "i" are valid.
A "b" operand causes SYSPUB to generate bullets for all points at the
level for which it is specified.
(If the output is being produced at an on-line terminal, asterisks are
generated instead of bullets.)
If a character other than one of "1", "a", "i", or "b" is specified,
then that character will be used in a fashion similar to that for "bulle
.subsection 'Limitations'
..pp;There are a few things to keep in mind when using the above
point-generating SYSPUB commands.
.point begin
The "point" commands
automatically indent the left and right margins, so that
the text of the points are "set in" from the main text.
Therefore, if you wish to use the SCRIPT ".in" INDENT control word in a
point, use the additive rather than the absolute form of the arguments.
.point
It is possible to use ".point end" to return from "point mode" temporari
(for example, to explain something about the preceding or following
points) and then resume the "point mode" without interrupting the
numbering sequence of the list of points.
..ix 2 numbering points
In this case, after the text for the
"normal mode" has been specified, the list of points can be continued
by using the SYSPUB command ".point" instead of ".point begin".
.point end
For example, the text of the above point was terminated with ".point end
and the text of the next point was started with ".point" rather than
with ".point begin".
.point
If you want to alter the formatting environment for all the points
..ix 2 points 'altering the format'
generated between the
".point begin" and ".point end" commands, do it immediately
before the ".point begin" command.  For example, if the normal formattin
mode is "double-spaced and right-justified", but you want the text of th
points to be single-spaced and not right-justified, you can specify
..sp;     ,ss;.ju no;.point begin
..sp;and then the text for the first point.
The ".point end" command will restore the default formatting parameters.
(The ",ss" above is a "no-break single space" control word;
the comma is established as the no-break contro word indicator
when you imbed SYSPUB -- see Appendix A for more details).
.point end
.section 'Boxes'
..ix 2 boxes
..ix boxon;..ix boxoff
..pp;The two SYSPUB commands ".boxon" and ".boxoff" may be
used to start and terminate a box.
For example,
..sp;..cc 5
     .boxon
     This text is surrounded by a box which
     was created by the ".boxon" and
     ".boxoff" commands.
     .boxoff
..sp;produces:
..cc begin
.boxon
This text is surrounded by a box which
was created by the ".boxon" and
".boxoff" commands.
.boxoff
..cc end
..pp;The conditions which must be adhered to and the restrictions which
exist within the range of ".boxon" and ".boxoff" are defined below.
.point begin
The left side of the box will be generated one position to the right of
the current SCRIPT ".in" INDENT value.  The right side of the box
will be generated in the last position of the output line, as defined
by the current value of the SCRIPT ".ll" LINE LENGTH value
modified by the current "right-indent" value of the SCRIPT ".in"
INDENT control word.
.point;You may use the SCRIPT ".bx" control word to create "horizontal
lines" within the range of ".boxon" and ".boxoff".
.point;If you wish to use the SCRIPT ".in" indent control word
..ix 2 boxes 'indenting inside'
within the range of ".boxon" and ".boxoff", then use
the additive rather than the absolute form of the arguments; for example
use ".in +5" rather than ".in 5".  This is necessary because of the SCRI
".in" control words issued by ".boxon" and ".boxoff":
..sp;..cc 2
     .boxon  issues  ..in +3 -3
     .boxoff issues  ..in -3 +3
.point
The SYSPUB ".boxon" and ".boxoff" commands, by themselves, make no
attempt to keep the box from being split over a page boundary.
If you do not want it split
across a page boundary,
then use the SCRIPT ".cc" or ".fk" or ".fb"
control words to ensure that the box is contiguous.  If you use
".fb" or ".fk", or ".cc" in its "begin/end" form to do this,
do not rely on the values of any of the SCRIPT
system reference variables such as "&syspage" or "&sysline" within the
range of ".boxon" and ".boxoff", as there is no
guarantee that the box will print in the position in which it was
formatted; use ".cc" with a numeric argument instead.
.point end
.section 'Tables'
..ix 2 tables
..pp;Turabian [1973:159] makes an excellent statement concerning
the attention you must give to tables if you are going to use them
effectively:
.quote begin
If tables are to serve satisfactorily the purpose for which they are mad
they not only must be accurately compiled but must be so arranged that
they can be easily read and interpreted.
To these ends careful spacing, ruling, arrangement of headings, and,
finally, the placing of the tables
with respect to the text all contribute.
.quote end
..pp;The following SYSPUB commands
are used to construct tables.
The SYSPUB command ".tabnum" is used to generate the table number.
The SYSPUB command ".tabbegin" is used to start the definition of the te
and SCRIPT control words which create the table.
The SYSPUB command ".table"
is used to print the table number and title; and the SYSPUB command
".tabend" is used to end the definition of the table and to cause it to
positioned
for printing.  If the table will fit in the position at which you have
defined it, it will do so.  Otherwise, SCRIPT will promote it to another
page (usually, the next page).
To give you a better idea of how these commands are used, consider the
following example;
the commands themselves are described in more detail following the examp
.subsection 'Example of a Table'
..pp;Assume that we now wish to make our
first reference to a particular table.
To begin, we will generate "the next available table number" and
assign it to the reference variable "example".
..sp;     .tabnum example
..sp;Then, we can use the reference variable "example" to make
the reference to the table.
..sp;..cc 2
     .ur As can be seen from Table &example.,
     the quality of ... (rest of sentence).
..sp;which will actually print as
..sp;..in 5 -5;.tabnum example
..ur As can be seen from Table &example.,
the quality of ... (rest of sentence).
..sp;..in 0;Then, at the end of the paragraph in which that sentence
appears, we can specify the text and the SCRIPT control words
and SYSPUB commands
required to generate, position, and print the table itself.
..sp
     .tabbegin
     .table example 'This is a Sample Table'
     first line of table
     second line of table
      .
      .
      .
     last line of table
     .tabend
..pp;The table which the above commands create is printed below.
The box around the table is
..us not;generated by the above commands; an explanation of how the box
was generated is given later in this chapter.
.tabbegin
.boxon
.table example 'This is a Sample Table'
first line of table
second line of table
 .
 .
 .
last line of table
.boxoff
.tabend
.subsection 'The Table Number'
..ix 2 numbering tables
..pp;A table should be positioned as soon as possible
..us after
the first reference to it in the text.  Since tables must be numbered
in ascending order throughout the publication, the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .tabnum refname
..ix tabnum
..sp;enables you to generate "the next available number"
for a table and assign that number to the reference variable "refname",
and then use "refname" to refer to the table in the text, before the
table is defined, constructed, and printed.
.subsection 'Positioning the Table'
..pp;It is desirable to print the table itself as soon as possible after
it has first been referenced in the text.
Therefore, at the end of the paragraph which contains the first referenc
to the table, the SYSPUB commands and SCRIPT control words required to
define the table should be inserted, starting with the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .tabbegin
..ix tabbegin
..sp;The ".tabbegin" command causes single-spacing to be in effect
and places you in unformatted mode.
The SYSPUB ".tabend" command described below restores the
formatting mode and the "line-spacing"
to whatever was in effect before ".tabbegin" was
encountered.
.subsection 'The Title of the Table'
..ix 2 headings table
..pp;The ".tabbegin" command should be followed by the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .table refname 'title of table'
..ix table
..sp;which prints the word "Table",
the value of "refname" (the table number), the title of the table, and
leaves you in ".fo no" mode.
It should then be followed by the text and SCRIPT control words needed t
construct the table (or to leave space in which to paste in the table, i
that is how it is to be done).
.subsection 'Terminating the Table'
..ix 2 tables 'full-page'
..pp;To terminate the table, the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .tabend
..ix tabend
..sp;must be inserted next.
It causes the table to be positioned and printed,
and restores the formatting environment for normal text.
Every attempt will be made to
keep the table contiguous on one page (unless the table requires more th
one page).
..pp;If you specify this command in the form
..sp;     .tabend page
..sp;then SYSPUB will add the number of blank lines required to
result in a full-page table.
..ix 'tabend' 'page'
..ix 'figend' 'page'
.subsection 'Limitations'
..pp;You cannot define a footnote within the range of a table.
Also, don't use the SCRIPT ".ix" index control
word within a table; it will most likely result in the wrong page number
in the index, since the table will probably print some other than where
where it was formatted.
.section 'Figures'
..ix 2 figures;..ix 2 figures . 'see also "tables"'
..pp;The considerations which must be given
to tables also apply to figures.
The SYSPUB commands for figures
are exact parallels of those defined above for tables, with the
exception that the ".figbegin" command leaves you in ".fo no" mode.
For example,
.fignum sampfig
..sp;..cc 12
     .fignum sampfig
     .figbegin
     first line of figure
     second line of figure
      .
      .
      .
     last line of figure
     .figure sampfig 'This is a Sample Figure'
     .figend
..ix fignum;..ix figbegin;..ix figure;..ix figend
..sk;..ur produces Figure &sampfig below.
Note that the text and SCRIPT control words
which define the figure are placed
..us before;the SYSPUB ".figure" command, whereas,
for a table, they are placed
..us after;the ".table" command.
.figbegin
.boxon
first line of figure
second line of figure
 .
 .
 .
last line of figure
.figure sampfig 'This is a Sample Figure'
.boxoff;.figend
..sp;..in 0;..fo
.section 'Calling Tables or Figures by Some Other Name'
..ix 2 tables 'calling them something else'
..pp;If you don't need to use both tables and figures in your
publication, you can make use of the
..us capabilites
of the SYSPUB commands for tables and figures to create other
entities.
..pp;For example, if your publication had a number of "examples", and
you wanted to have them handled the same way SYSPUB handles tables
and figures, you could instruct SYSPUB that your "figures" are
really "examples", by specifying
..sp;     .sr pubFIhdr = 'Example'
..sp;immediately after you imbed SYSPUB and before any of the SYSPUB
commands for the main body of the publication.
You would still use the SYSPUB commands for "figures", but they would
all be annotated as "examples" in the output.
..pp;Similarly, if you wanted tables to be called "illustrations", you
could do so by specifying
..sp;     .sr pubTAhdr = 'Illustration'
.section 'Putting a Box Around a Table or Figure'
..ix 2 boxes 'around a table or figure'
..pp;If it is appropriate to draw a box around a table or figure
(or whatever you are calling them)
to set it off, the two SYSPUB commands ".boxon" and ".boxoff" may be
used to create the box.  They were used, for example, to put the
..ur box around Table &example..
The ".boxon"
..ix boxon;command was placed immediately after the ".tabbegin"
command, and the ".boxoff"
..ix boxoff;command was placed immediately before the ".tabend" command.
.chapter 'The PAPER Layout'
..ix 2 layouts PAPER
..pp;The PAPER layout provides all of the commands available with REPORT
but in a layout style more suited
to small research publications, technical papers, or term papers.
The various levels of divisions of the "main body"
are numbered (such as "1.2" for the second "section" in the first "chapt
.tabnum layouts
..ur PAPER also provides the additional commands described in Table &lay
.tabbegin;.boxon
.table layouts 'PAPER Layout Commands'
..ce 1
 .im syspub layout=paper
..sp;..bx;..sp
..co;..ju no
..tb set !;..tb 19
..of 19
 .prelim!for preliminary material,
such as an abstract or acknowledgement
..br;..of 19
 .appendix!to create appendices
..br;..of 19
 .bibliography!to start a bibliography
..br;..of 19
 .bib!to start a bibliographic entry
..of;..tb set
.boxoff;.tabend
.section 'Preliminary Material'
..ix 2 'preliminary sections'
..pp;Any "preliminary" material which the paper requires
may be generated by using the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .prelim 'title'
..ix prelim
..pp;The two most obvious uses of the ".prelim" command are to generate
"abstract" and "acknowledgements" material, such as
..sp;     .prelim 'Abstract'
..sp;followed by the text of the abstract, and
..sp;     .prelim 'Acknowledgements'
..sp;followed by the text of the acknowledgements.
.section 'Starting an Appendix'
..ix 2 appendixes
..pp;An appendix is generated in exactly the same way as a chapter, by
using the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .appendix 'title'
..ix appendix
.section 'The Bibliography'
..ix 2 bibliography
..pp;The SYSPUB command
..sp;     .bibliography
..ix bibliography
..sp;starts the formatting of the bibliography.
If the word "BIBLIOGRAPHY" is not an appropriate header for the
bibliography, then use
..sp;     .bibliography 'alternate header'
..sp;where "alternate header", for example, might be something
like "Sources Consulted".
.subsection 'Starting a Bibliographic Entry'
..ix 2 bibliography entries
..ix bib
..pp;Each of the bibliographic entries is started with the SYSPUB comman
..sp;     .bib
..sp;If you do not have a style to which you must adhere, then
it is suggested that the following general form be used to enter the tex
for the bibliographic entry.
..sp;..cc 4
     .bib
     last name of author, first name, initials.
     .us title of reference.
     place of publication:  publisher, year.
..pp;You do not need to specify any SCRIPT control words for the
formatting of the bibliographic entries;
the ".bib" command does that for you (see the Bibliography
at the end of this User's Guide for an example of the formatting).
..pp;In order to keep the text for a bibliographic entry on one page,
SYSPUB internally places a SCRIPT ".cc" begin/end sequence around the
text of the bibliographic entry.
This means that you cannot use ".cc", ".cp", ".fk", ".fn", or ".fb" in
conjunction with the SYSPUB commands for the bibliography.
.subsection 'Terminating the Bibliography'
..ix 'bib end'
..pp;The text of the
..us last
bibliographic reference must be followed by the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .bib end
.subsection 'Referencing Bibliographic Entries'
..ix 2 bibliography references
..pp;In the main body of the text,
bibliographic entries are referenced simply by specifying the
author's last name followed by the date of the publication and the
the appropriate page number(s) in the publication, as suggested by
Turabian[1973:182-183].
.fignum egbibli
..pp;..ur The example in Figure &egbibli is taken from the Bibliography
for this SYSPUB User's Guide.
For an alternate method, see Appendix B.
.figbegin;.boxon;..li >
.bibliography
.bib
.us Introduction to SCRIPT.
Waterloo:
University of Waterloo Computing Centre, 1977.
.bib
.us MLA Style Sheet.
2nd ed.  New York:
Modern Language Association of America, 1970.
.bib end
>>li .
.figure egbibli 'Input For a Sample Bibliography'
.boxoff;.figend
.section 'Creating Additional Pages After the Main Body'
..pp;The ".prelim" command can also be used to create additional pages
after the main body of the publication.
.chapter 'The GUIDE Layout'
..ix 2 layouts GUIDE
..pp;With layouts lesser than GUIDE, SYSPUB does not produce a Table of
Contents, and hence is somewhat less expensive to use.
With the GUIDE layout (or greater), SYSPUB includes the titles of
preliminary pages, chapters, appendices, sections, subsections, and
subsubsections in the Table of Contents, together with the titles
specified by the commands introduced in this chapter.
It also constructs a List of Tables and a List of Figures, using the
titles specified by the SYSPUB commands which create tables and figures.
..pp;The GUIDE layout is intended for papers which are large enough to
warrant a Table of Contents and/or an Index, or for other medium-sized
documents which do not warrant starting each chapter on a new page.
It is assumed that there will be at least one section created by the
".prelim" command (subsequent occurrences do not start new pages),
followed by one or more sections created by ".chapter" (only the first
chapter will begin on a new page), followed by zero or more sections
created by ".appendix" (each appendix starts on a new page),
..us possibly;followed by the additional commands introduced
.tabnum layouts
..ur in Table &layouts..
.tabbegin;.boxon
.table layouts 'GUIDE Layout Commands'
..ce 1
 .im syspub layout=guide
..sp;..bx;..sp
..co;..ju no
..tb set !;..tb 19
 .index!to print an index
 .contents!to print a table of contents
 .tables!to print a "list of tables"
 .figures!to print a "list of figures"
..tb set
.boxoff;.tabend
.section 'The Index'
..ix 2 index entries
..pp;If it is appropriate that your publication contain an index, then
you should use the SCRIPT ".ix" control word
to create the index entries, as they occur in the text
of your publication.
If you do not want your publication to have an index, ignore this sectio
.subsection 'Printing the Index'
..ix 2 index
..pp;At the end of the main body of the publication,
use the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .index
..ix index
..sp;to cause the index to be printed.  The word "INDEX" will be
centred at the top of the first page of the index.
.subsection 'Publications With More Than One Index'
..ix index 'more than one index'
..pp;If it is appropriate that your publication contain more than one
index (the SCRIPT ".ix" control word allows you to construct up to nine
concurrently), then each index can be printed by specifying the SYSPUB
command
..sp;     .index n 'title'
..sp;once for each index, where "n" is the index number (from 1 to 9)
and "title" is the title to be centred at the top of the first page of
index "n".
..pp;Note that this form of the ".index" command may also be used to
specify an alternate title for a publication which contains only one
index, by specifying
..sp;     .index 1 'title'
.subsection 'Printing the Index in Multiple-Column Mode'
..ix 2 index 'multiple-column output'
..pp;By default, the index will be printed in single-column mode, the
same as the rest of the publication.
If your index entries are short, you may wish to have them printed in
more than one column per page.
For example,
..sp;     .index n 'title' 2
..sp;will cause the index to be printed in two columns.
You can specify a number larger than "2" for this third operand, but you
may run into problems unless you have used the "ll" parameter to specify
a line length greater than the default when you imbedded SYSPUB.
.section 'The Table of Contents'
..ix 2 'contents'
..ix 2 headings 'table of contents'
..pp;The Table of Contents includes the titles and page numbers
of any titles generated
by the SYSPUB commands ".prelim", ".part", ".chapter", ".appendix",
".section", ".subsection", ".subsub",
".bibliography", and ".index".
For chapters and appendices, the chapter and appendix numbers are printe
to the left of the titles.
.subsection 'Printing the Table of Contents'
..ix contents
..pp;The "contents" command causes the printing of the Table of Contents
It is of the form
..sp;     .contents 'alternate header'
..sp;where "alternate header" is any character string you wish
to use as the title of the Table of Contents.  If you do not specify an
"alternate header", then the header "TABLE OF CONTENTS" will be used.
..pp;Unless you have tables or figures, ".contents" will be the last SYS
command in your input file.
The resulting Table of Contents pages will be numbered in lower-case
roman numerals, starting one greater than the last "preliminary page"
before the main body.
You will have to remove these Table of Contents pages from the end of
the output and insert them in their proper place.
.subsection 'Printing the List of Tables'
..ix 2 tables 'list of tables'
..ix 2 headings 'list of tables'
..ix tables
..pp;If the publication contains tables, the SYSPUB command ".tables"
should be used to cause the printing of the List of Tables.
It is of the form
..sp;     .tables 'alternate header'
..sp;where "alternate header" is any character string you wish
to use as the title of the List of Tables.  If you do not specify an
"alternate header", then the header "LIST OF TABLES" will be used.
.subsection 'Printing the List of Figures'
..ix 2 figures 'list of figures'
..ix 2 headings 'list of figures'
..ix figures
..pp;If the publication contains figures, the SYSPUB command
".figures" should be used to cause the printing of the List of Figures.
It is of the form
..sp;     .figures 'alternate header'
..sp;where "alternate header" is any character string you wish
to use as the title of the List of Figures.  If you do not specify an
"alternate header", then the header "LIST OF FIGURES" will be used.
.chapter 'The MANUAL Layout'
..ix 2 layouts MANUAL
..pp;The MANUAL layout is intended for documents which are large enough
warrant a formal title page and a number of preliminary pages.
If the document is large enough,
chapters may be grouped together in "parts".
Preliminary pages, parts, chapters, and appendices
each start on a new page.
.tabnum layouts
..ur The additional SYSPUB commands are shown in Table &layouts..
.tabbegin;.boxon
.table layouts 'MANUAL Layout Commands'
..ce 1
 .im syspub layout=manual
..sp;..bx;..sp
..co;..ju no
..tb set !;..tb 19
 .part!to group chapters into "parts"
..tb set
.boxoff;.tabend
.section 'The Title Page'
..ix 2 'title page'
..pp;With the MANUAL layout, the text which follows the ".titlepage" com
will appear on a "title page" by itself.
This page will be page "i" of the publication, although it will not
have a page number printed on it.
The other "preliminary pages" of the publication, if any, will be
numbered at the bottom of each page, beginning with "ii".
.section 'Parts'
..ix 2 headings parts
..ix 2 parts
..pp;If the main body of the publication is large enough that it warrant
being separated into "parts", then the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .part 'title'
..ix part
..sp;may be used to generate each of the "part" title pages.
The word "PART", the part number (in upper-case roman numerals), and the
part title will be centered on an unnumbered page by themselves.
The part title will print in uppercase on the part-title page, but will
added to the Table of Contents as you specified it.
.section 'Chapters'
..ix 2 headings chapter
..pp;Each first-level division started by the ".chapter" command will be
on a new page, with the word "Chapter" and the chapter number
centered at the top of the page, and the title of the chapter centered
below.
.subsection 'Calling the "Chapters" by Some Other Name'
..ix 2 chapters 'calling them something else'
..pp;In some publications, the term "chapter" may not be appropriate,
and therefore you may want some word other than "Chapter" to
be used as a "header"
at the beginning of each "chapter".
For example, if you specify
..sp;     .major 'Section'
..ix 'major'
..sp;immediately before the
first occurence of ".chapter", SYSPUB will print the
word "Section" at the top of the first page of each "chapter".
Note that you must still use the
".chapter" command to create the major divisions of your publication,
even though you are calling them something else.
.section 'Example'
.fignum outline
..pp;..ur Figure &outline illustrates the organization of the input
file for the "manual" layout.
.figbegin;.boxon
 .im syspub layout=manual
 .titlepage
 THIS IS THE TITLE OF THE MANUAL
      .
      . other lines for the title page
      .
 .prelim 'Abstract'
 .chapter 'Introduction'
      .
      .
      .
 .appendix 'other stuff'
 .contents
 .tables
 .figures
.figure outline 'Sample Input File Using The MANUAL Layout'
.boxoff;.figend
.chapter 'The REFMAN Layout'
..pp;The REFMAN layout has not yet been fully implemented or tested.
It is intended to produce output identical to that of MANUAL except
for the numbering of pages, tables, and figures.
It also assumes that the document is to be published on both sides of th
page.
..cc begin;.boxon
..ju no
 .im syspub layout=refman
.boxoff;..cc end
.chapter 'The THESIS Layout'
..ix 2 layouts THESIS
..pp;The THESIS layout produces output
.footnote identical
Chapter numbers will normally be printed as upper-case roman numerals.
However,
if the ".part" command has been used before the first ".chapter" command
encountered, then chapter numbers are printed as arabic numerals to avoi
confusion.
.footend
..ix 2 numbering chapters
to that of the MANUAL
.tabnum layouts
..ur layout, and provides the commands shown in Table &layouts to create
the additional preliminary pages required in a thesis.
.tabbegin;.boxon
.table layouts 'THESIS Layout Commands'
..ce 1
 .im syspub layout=thesis
..sp;..bx;..sp
..co;..ju no
..tb set !;..tb 19
..of 19
 .author!to specify and position
the name of the author on the title page
..of 19
 .course!to specify the name of the course
for which the document is begin submitted, or
..of 19
 .degree!to specify the name of the degree
for which the thesis is being submitted
..of 19
 .date!to generate the date and copyright lines
..of 19
 .declaration!creates the "author's declaration" page
..of 19
 .borrow!creates the "borrower's page"
..of;..tb set
.boxoff;.tabend
.section 'Additional Commands for the Title Page'
..ix 2 'title page' 'for a thesis'
.subsection "The Author's Name"
..pp;The author's name is positioned and printed on the Title Page by us
the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .author 'full name of author'
..ix 'author'
..sk;It may be followed by any additional lines of text
needed to satisfy the requirements of the thesis.
..pp;If the author's name contains the apostrophe character ('), then
the ".author" command must be specified instead as
..sp;     .author "full name of author"
..sp;using the double-quote (") instead of apostrophes to delimit
the author's name.
.subsection 'Degree'
..pp;If the publication is being submitted as a thesis in fulfillment of
degree requirements, then use the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .degree 'title of degree'
..ix 'degree'
..sp;followed on the next input line(s) by the name of the department
granting the degree.
.subsection 'Course'
..pp;If the publication is not really a thesis but is being submitted
in partial fulfillment of
the requirements for a particular course, then use the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .course 'course code' 'title of course'
..ix 'course'
..sp;followed on the next input line(s) by any additional
relevant information you must supply about the course.
.subsection 'The Date of the Publication'
..ix 'date'
..pp;The ".date" command causes the "date" and "copyright" lines to be
printed at the bottom of the page.  It is of the form
..sp;     .date 'copyright symbol'
..sp;The "copyright symbol" is optional; if the command is used as ".dat
only, then the characters "(c)" will be used as the copyright symbol.
..pp;If the "date" and "copyright" lines which the ".date" command
produces are not appropriate for your publication, you can omit the
".date" command, and instead use the appropriate SCRIPT control words
and text lines.
.section "The Author's Declaration Page"
..ix 2 "author's declaration page"
..pp;Most theses must have some form of "author's declaration" page.
The SYSPUB command
..sp;     .declaration
..ix declaration
..sp;will generate such a page, with the appropriate words on it.
.section "The Borrower's Page"
..ix 2 "borrower's page"
..pp;A thesis must have a "borrower's page".
Such a page will be generated by the SYSPUB command
..sp;     .borrow
..ix borrow
.section 'Example'
.fignum outline1
..pp;..ur Figure &outline1 illustrates the organization of the input
file for a thesis.
.figbegin;.boxon
 .im syspub layout=thesis
 .titlepage
 THIS IS THE TITLE OF THE THESIS
 .author 'my name'
 .degree 'name of Degree'
 Department granting the Degree
 .date
 .declaration
 .borrow
 .prelim 'Abstract'
 .prelim 'Acknowledgements'
 .chapter 'Introduction'
 .chapter 'Hypothesis'
 .chapter 'Method'
 .chapter 'Observations'
 .chapter 'Conclusions'
 .appendix 'other stuff'
 .contents
 .tables
 .figures
.figure outline1 'Sample Input File Using The THESIS Layout'
.boxoff;.figend
.chapter 'Special Layouts'
..pp;Several special-purpose layouts are available with SYSPUB,
for layout styles particular to specific publishing groups.
SYSPUB currently has layouts for IEEE and APA.
.section 'The IEEE Layout'
..ix 2 layouts IEEE
..pp;The IEEE layout is intended for papers which are to be produced on
the grid sheets provided by the IEEE Editorial Department for
the preparation of papers in two-column format for IEEE photo-offset
publications.
It provides all of the SYSPUB commands which correspond to the PAPER
layout, with the differences and/or exceptions noted below:
.point begin
none of the headings produced by ".chapter", ".section", or ".subsection
will be numbered;
.point
titles produced by ".chapter" will be centred,
underscored, and capitalized;
.point
titles produced by ".section" will underscored and printed flush with th
left margin, exactly as entered;
.point
titles printed by ".subsection" will be underscored and indented as
the starting text in a new paragraph.
.point end
