the parameter "lpi=8" on the ".im syspub" command.
.section 'The APA Layouts'
..pp;There are two layouts which conform to
the style of the American Psychological Association.
They provide all of the SYSPUB commands which correspond to the THESIS
layout, with the differences and/or exceptions noted below:
.point begin
headings for the various divisions in the main body will not be numbered
or named;
.point
layout APA4 supports four levels of divisions of the text:
..ix 2 layouts APA4
.point 2
titles produced by ".chapter" will be in uppercase, centered, and will
start on a new page;
.point
titles produced by ".section" will underscored, centered, and printed as
entered;
.point
titles produced by ".subsection" will be underscored and printed flush
with the left margin, exactly as entered;
.point
titles produced by ".subsub" will be underscored and indented as
the starting text in a new paragraph, exactly as entered.
.point 1
layout APA3 supports three levels of divisions of the text:
..ix 2 layouts APA3
.point 2
titles produced by ".chapter" will be underscored, centered, and printed
as is;
.point
titles produced by ".section" will be underscored and printed flush
with the left margin, exactly as entered;
.point
titles produced by ".subsection" will be underscored and indented as
the starting text in a new paragraph, exactly as entered.
.point end
.appendix 'CHANGING THE FORMAT OF THE PUBLICATION'
.section 'Top and Bottom Margins and Titles'
..pp;If you wish your publication to have a TOP MARGIN or BOTTOM MARGIN
..ix 2 'page layout' 'top and bottom margins'
different than those which are the SCRIPT defaults, then specify
the SCRIPT ".tm" and/or ".bm" control words
..us before ×you imbed SYSPUB.
SYSPUB will fail to work properly if you
re-define them once SYSPUB has been imbedded.
..pp;SYSPUB, by default, removes from you all
..ix 2 'page layout' 'top and bottom titles'
control over the number of title lines in the top and bottom
margins, because it constantly issues its own SCRIPT ".hs" and ".fs"
control words
as it is deciding when to print the top and
bottom title lines.
You can re-define the top and bottom title after you imbed SYSPUB,
but SYSPUB will decide when to print the top title and when to
print the bottom title.
If you wish to define any number of top and bottom title lines which are
..us always ×to be printed at the top and bottom of each and every page,
then do the following
..us before ×you imbed SYSPUB:
..sp;..cc begin
     .sr pubMYhs = number of top title lines desired
     .sr pubMYfs = number of bottom title lines desired
     then define the top and bottom title lines
..cc end
..sp;If you do this, you must define at least one of each.
.section 'Controlling Entries in the Table of Contents'
..ix 2 contents 'controlling what goes in it'
..pp;By default, section (second-level), subsection (third-level), and
subsubsection (fourth-level)
headings are included in the Table of Contents.  You can control the lev
of inclusion by setting the value of the "inclusion level", with the
SCRIPT control word
..sp;     .sr pubSWinc = value
..sp;A value of "4" or greater will cause section, subsection, and
subsubsection headings to be included in the Table of
Contents; this is the default.  A value of "1" will cause
chapter and appendix (first-level)
headings to be included, but section,
subsection, and subsubsection headings will be
omitted from the Table of Contents.
..pp;For example, if you wish to have all subsubsection headings omitted
from the Table of Contents, then the SCRIPT control word
..sp;     .sr pubSWinc = 3
..sp;should be specified before the first occurrence of the SYSPUB
command ".subsub".
..pp;If you wish to omit the subsection and subsubsection headings from
the Table of Contents for
a particular chapter (or range of chapters), then specify the SCRIPT
control word
..sp;     .sr pubSWinc = 2
..sp;before the occurrence of the SYSPUB ".chapter" command which
defines the first chapter for which you want them
omitted, and then specify the SCRIPT control word
..sp;     .sr pubSWinc = 4
..sp;at the very end of the chapter (or at the very end of the
last chapter in the range of chapters) for which you want
them to be omitted from the Table of Contents.
.section 'Changing The Numbering Styles'
.subsection 'Parts, Chapters, and Appendices'
..ix 2 numbering parts;..ix 2 numbering chapters;..ix 2 numbering append
..pp;If you do not like the default numbering styles, you can change any
all by inserting the SCRIPT control words
..sp;..cc 3
     .sr pubPAnar = 'new style'
     .sr pubCHnar = 'new style'
     .sr pubAPnar = 'new style'
..sp;before the first occurence of ".part", ".chapter", or ".appendix"
respectively.  The "new style" must be one of the choices
..sp;..cc 3
     arabic
     roman upper
     theatre       (don't use this for chapters)
..sp;"Theatre" numbering results in the sequence "A", "B", ..., "Z".
.subsection 'Footnotes'
..ix 2 numbering footnotes
..pp;You can force the footnote numbering to be done independent of the
ONLINE or OFFLINE output mode by specifying one of the following before
the first occurence of the ".footnote" command.
Specifying
..sp;     .sr pubfnsup = 'nosup'
..sp;will force the footnote numbers
..ul 1 not;to be generated as superscripts.  Instead, they will be
generated as though the output mode was ONLINE.  Specifying
..sp;     .sr pubfnsup = 'sup'
..sp;will force the footnote numbers to be generated as superscripts eve
if the output mode is ONLINE.
.section 'Special Considerations'
..pp;There are a number of things which SYSPUB does internally with whic
you may not interfere.
They are presented below in terms of the SCRIPT control words on which
they depend.
.subsection 'Control Word Separator (cw)'
..pp;All SYSPUB commands with the exception of those for footnotes deman
..sp;     .cw ;
..sp;be in effect.
.subsection 'Control Word Indicator Literal (li)'
..pp;SYSPUB establishes the period (.) as the control word indicator lit
and the comma (,) as the
..ul 1 nobreak;control word indicator literal.
These must be in effect whenever a SYSPUB command is encountered
and also must be in effect whenever several circumstances over which
you have no control
.footnote occur.
SYSPUB causes a number of "internal" commands to be invoked
automatically (for example, at the top of each page, SYSPUB checks to se
there are any tables or figures to be printed).
.footend
This means that the only time it is
..us safe
for you to change the control word indicator is in the "begin/end" range
a block of text defined by the ".cc" or ".fk" or ".fn" SCRIPT control wo
Disasterous results will occur in other circumstances.
.subsection 'Remote (rm)'
..pp;SYSPUB issues a "first line of the text area" REMOTE using
..sp;     .rm *
..sp;Therefore, you cannot; nor can you change the TOP MARGIN (tm) value
after you imbed SYSPUB.
.subsection 'Translate on Input (ti)'
..pp;For your convenience, SYSPUB defines
a translate table which will map the digits 0 through 9 into
their superscript equivalents.  All you need to do to take advantage of
this is to use the "set" operand of ".ti" to define an escape
character.
For example, if you specify
..sp;     .ti set #
..sp;as the "translate on input" escape character,
then an input line containing the characters
..sp;     The quantity "x squared" is written as x#2.
..sp;will print on the high-speed line printer as
..ti set #
..sp;     The quantity "x squared" is written as x#2.
..br;..ti set
.subsection 'Underscore, Underscore and Capitalize (us,uc)'
..pp;SYSPUB establishes the vertical bar (×) as the "escape" character
which turns underscoring off and on in the ".us" and ".uc" operand lines
by issuing a
..sp;     .ud set ×
.appendix 'AN ALTERNATE METHOD FOR BIBLIOGRAPHIES'
..ix 2 bibliography
..pp;The material below describes a method for preparing the Bibliograph
which is not often recommended because it is cumbersome.
It may not be used with a layout less than MANUAL.
.section 'Entering the Bibliographic Entries'
..ix 2 bibliography entries
..pp;The bibliography, if present in a publication, is placed at the end
publication (unless there is an index).
However, to allow you to reference the bibliographic entries with symbol
references instead of absolute numbers,
the SYSPUB commands to format the bibliography can be entered
immediately after the SYSPUB commands for the title page and immediately
before the SYSPUB command for the preliminary pages (or parts and chapte
if there are no preliminary pages).
If you do this, you must use the ".bib" command in the form
..sp;     .bib refname
..ix bib
..sp;where "refname" is a unique one- to eight-character "reference name
which the author assigns.
Bibliographic reference numbers
will be generated automatically and printed to the left of each referenc
.section 'Referencing Bibliographic Entries'
..ix 2 bibliography references
..pp;In the main body of the publication, the "refname"  may be used
to refer to the bibliographic entry by specifying the
"refname" followed by a period followed by a colon followed by
the appropriate page number(s) in the reference.
For example, if "turabian" were the "refname" assigned to the publicatio
Turabian (see the Bibliography for this SYSPUB User's Guide), then
it could be referenced in the form
..sp;     .ur [&turabian.:182-183]
..sp;to reference the pages in that publication which describe this meth
The number assigned to the bibliographic entry by the
".bib" command is substituted automatically for "refname" (in this case,
"turabian").
Therefore, if bibliographic entries are added to or deleted from the
bibliography during the writing of the publication, there is no need to
to worry about using the proper "reference number" in the main body of t
paper.
.appendix 'OTHER SYSPUB REFERENCE VARIABLES'
..pp;The following SYSPUB reference variables may be of some use to you.
..sp
..in 10
..oo 1 pubXXnum
where "XX" is one of the following two-letter combinations:
..sp;..in +5
..fo no
BI   bibliographic entry number
FN   footnote number
CH   chapter number
FI   figure number
PA   part number
PO   point number
SE   section number
SS   subsubsection number
SU   subsection number
TA   table number
..in -5;..sp;..fo
For example, if you want to save the current chapter number for referenc
later in the document, then:
..sp
     .chapter 'title of chapter'
     .se thischap = &pubCHnum
          .
          .
          .
     As was previously mentioned in
     .ur Chapter &thischap., we ...
..sp
..oo 1 pubSWprt
contains the current chapter (or appendix), section, subsection,
and subsubsection numbers
as a character string of the form
..sp;..in +5;chapter.section.subsection.subsubsection
..sp;..in -5
..in 10;..oo 1 pubSWtop
is the number of lines to be skipped at the top of the title page, the f
page of the bibliography, the declaration page, and the first page creat
by each occurrence of the ".prelim", ".chapter", ".appendix", ".contents
".tables", ".figures", and ".index" commands.
..ur Its default value is &pubSWtop., but it can be changed by specifyin
..sp;     .sr pubSWtop = number of spaces desired
..sp;SCRIPT control word immediately before invoking the SYSPUB command
to which you want it to apply.  The new value will be used by all of the
above SYSPUB commands encountered thereafter, until you change it again.
..sp;..in 10;..oo 1 pubSWbtw
is the number of lines skipped before a section, subsection, or item, an
before and after a table or figure.  You can change it the same way you
change "pubSWtop", with the same resultant effect.
..ur Its default value is &pubSWbtw..
